        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Sep 23. 1873</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Many thanks for your renewed kindness. I have written to Dr Moore to ask him to prepare some fibrin for me &amp; to test its purity from Hydro chloric acid &amp; all salts. As he has been accustomed to prepare animal compounds, I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> think he might be quite trusted. I told him that you were going to test for the acid.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>I procured doubly distilled water from Mess<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Hopkins &amp; Williams.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> It is not free from particles when viewed in a strong light, &amp; when evaporated, leaves a little residue. I put a drop on a glass plate &amp; added a little weak nitrate of silver, &amp; I could see no trace of a cloud, so I hope it is sufficiently pure.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>As soon as I get the fibrin I will set to work with the leaves.</p>
<p>Yours sincerely obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9062.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Edward Frankland, 22 September 1873</ref>. CD’s letter to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6370.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Samuel William Moore</ref> has not been found, but he had already received casein from Moore (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9061A.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Edward Frankland, 21 September [1873]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Hopkin &amp; Williams was a firm of manufacturing chemists with premises at 10 New Cavendish Street, London (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6380.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Post Office London directory</hi></ref> 1872).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Silver nitrate reacts with chlorides in water to form a cloudy white precipitate (silver chloride).</note>
        </div>        
            
